shire, England":"Bradenstoke, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Cooling, Kent, England":"Cooling, Kent, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":35,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Malmayns was born about 1180, in Waldershare, Kent, England, his father, Gilbert Malmayns, was 23 and his mother, Aliénor de   Vitre, was 23. He married Joan Crispin de Tillières in 1198, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died about 1219, in Headley, Surrey, England, at the age of 41, and was buried in Bradenstoke, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1180–about 1219":"umbes 1180–umbes 1219","1180–1219":"1180–1219","1175–1237":"1175–1237","1180–1250":"1180–1250","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1204–1240":"1204–1240","1158–1217":"1158–1217","1158–1233":"1158–1233","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1198":"1198","Abt 1204":"umbes 1204","1175":"1175"